      <hedline>
        <hl1>Big Tobacco, Duly Punished?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Steve Schindler letter on July 15 article cites flaw in case against tobacco industry</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Tobacco Lawsuit in Florida Yields Record Damages'' (front page, July 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Tobacco Lawsuit in Florida Yields Record Damages'' (front page, July 15):</p>
        <p>There is a huge flaw in the case against the tobacco industry. It stands accused of withholding information from the public about the harmful effects of its product. This assumes that there is a causal link between information and human behavior. Yet millions of people have started smoking since the details about the harmful effects of smoking came to light. Can the sick smokers in Florida prove that they would have behaved differently had the industry behaved differently?</p>
        <p>STEVE SCHINDLER  New York, July 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
